  "title": "Belief Polarity Constellation",
  "story": [
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "aeb784b7f79e0aae",
      "text": "The belief-polarity constellation goes back to a classification scheme from the philosophy of religion by [[Frithjof Schuon]] (cf. e.g. Schuon 1981). Schuon uses a classification of yoga forms going back to Patanjali, the author of the classical yoga sutras, and the subsequent later yoga philosophy, in which the various training paths within the yoga system are based on three fundamental forms: [[Jnana]] yoga or the yoga of knowledge, [[Bhakti]] yoga or the yoga of love, and [[Karma]] yoga or the yoga of duty and action."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "65e075a811cd483c",
      "text": "Schuon now used this division of Patanjali to categorize forms of religion. According to him, the jnana, bhakti and karma aspects must be validly represented in every religion. If one of these aspects is not sufficiently taken into account, the corresponding form of religion degenerates."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "f99ac9418905355e",
      "text": "For didactic reasons, one of these aspects is usually emphasized in the world religions, such as the bhakti aspect in Christianity, the karma aspect in Judaism and the jnana aspect in Islam. Of course, the other aspects are also represented in these religions. So-called fundamentalists generally overemphasize one aspect and exclude the other aspects. For example, some so-called Islamic fundamentalists emphasize the karma aspect, often forgetting the bhakti and jnana aspects."
    },
